1 Question 1

1.1 Question of interest/goal of the study

Our goal is to build a model which can predict an athletes speed based on their step rate on an exercise track.

1.2 Read in and inspect the data:

StepT.df=read.table("StepTrack.txt",header=TRUE)

plot(SpeedT~StepT,main="Speed vs Step Rate for Track", xlab="Step Rate",
ylab="Speed",data=StepT.df)

1.3 Comment on Plot

There appears to be a strong, linear, positive relationship between Spend and Step rate on the track. When the athlete runs faster, he tends to have a higher step rate. Scatter remains constant and low throughout the range and there are no obvious outliers or groups/gaps.

1.4 Fit model and generate output

speed.fit<-lm(SpeedT ~ StepT, data=StepT.df) 
summary(speed.fit)

plot(speed.fit, which=1)

normcheck(speed.fit)

1.5 Plot with superimposed model

plot(SpeedT~StepT,main="Speed vs Step Rate for Track", xlab="Step Rate",
ylab="Speed",data=StepT.df)
abline(speed.fit, col ="red")

1.6 Method and Assumption Checks

A scatter plot of athlete Speed vs Step Rate showed a linear relationship with approximately constant scatter so a linear model was fitted.

The EOV, normality and linearity assumptions appear well satisfied. The residuals remain very closely distributed, the largest Cooks distance is only ~0.15 and QQ plot is very close to linear.

We assume that the readings are independent (e.g.the athlete is allowed sufficient rest between trials that each does not affect the others).

Our final model is \[ Speed_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \times StepRate_i + \epsilon_i\] Where \[\epsilon_i \;\tilde\;\; iid\;\:N(0,\sigma^2)\]

Our model explains 98% of the variation in speed, which is excellent.

1.7 Executive Summary

We collected data on the speed and step rate of an athlete performing speed runs on a track. Our goal was to see how speed and step rate are related, so that we can predict an athletes speed based on their step rate.

We found the higher the step rate of the athlete, the faster his speed in that run. There was strong evidence of this; we fitted a traditional linear model, and the data appeared to match the model. We estimate that every extra step taken per second increased the athletes running speed by about 14.1 km/h.

Using our model, we predict that if an athlete ran at rate of 4 steps per second, they would travel at between 26.1 and 29.2 km/h

2 Question 2

2.1 Question of interest/goal of the study

We are interested in the relationship between the speed of an athlete and his rate of steps per second during a game of football. Our goal is to build a model to predict the athletes speed from their step rate

2.2 Read in and inspect the data:

StepG.df=read.table("StepGame.txt",header=TRUE)

plot(SpeedG~StepG,main="Speed vs Step Rate for Game", xlab="Step Rate",
ylab="Speed",data=StepG.df)

2.3 Comment on Plot

There appears to be a strong, positive relationship between the step rate and speed of an athlete during a game of football. Scatter remains constant throughout the range and there are no noticeable outliers or gaps in the data. Again, as step rate increases the athletes speed also increases. However, in this case from visual inspection we cannot confidently state that the relationship is linear. There is a steep increase to start with and then the rate of increase slows.

2.4 Fit model and generate output

First, trying a linear model

speedG.fit<-lm(SpeedG ~ StepG, data=StepG.df) 
summary(speedG.fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = SpeedG ~ StepG, data = StepG.df)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max

plot(speedG.fit, which=1)

normcheck(speedG.fit)

cooks20x(speedG.fit)

We see that our residuals vary as step rate increases. Comparing with a quadratic model:

StepG.df$StepG2 <- StepG.df$StepG^2
speedG.fit2<-lm(SpeedG ~ StepG + StepG2, data=StepG.df) 
summary(speedG.fit2)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = SpeedG ~ StepG + StepG2, data = StepG.df)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -4.7400 -1.3567 -0.1538  1.3583  6.2585 
## 
## Coefficients:

## Multiple R-squared:  0.8566, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8562 
## F-statistic:  1918 on 2 and 642 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
plot(speedG.fit2, which=1)

normcheck(speedG.fit2)

cooks20x(speedG.fit2)

The quadratic model significantly improves the distribution of our residuals from our fitted values, as well as improving the R-squared. For these reasons, quadratic is likely the better model.

2.5 Plot with superimposed model

plot(SpeedG~StepG,main="Speed vs Step Rate for Game", xlab="Step Rate",
ylab="Speed",data=StepG.df)

# Hint. lines(x,y) connects up all the consecutive points from x[1],y[1] to x[2],y[2] to...
# Create a vector x over the desired range. The seq command is useful. Try seq(5,10,0.1) to see how it works
# Once you have an appropriate x vector, calculate the y values from your model for x.

StepRates <- seq(2,4,0.01)
PredictedSpeed <- predict(speedG.fit2,list(StepG = StepRates, StepG2 = StepRates^2))
lines(StepRates, PredictedSpeed, col ="red")

2.6 Plot with both superimposed models

plot(SpeedG~StepG,type="n",main="Speed vs Step Rate: Both Models", 
     xlab="Step Rate",ylab="Speed",data=StepG.df)

lines(StepRates, PredictedSpeed, col ="red")
abline(speed.fit, col ="blue" )
legend(3.3,14,legend = c("Quadratic - Game", "Linear - Track"), col = c("red","blue"), lty = 1:2)

2.7 Method and Assumption Checks

We fitted a linear model to the data, but our residuals as well as the scatter plot suggested this did not fit well. Since points with higher step rate gradually fell below the line, we attempted to fit a quadratic model. Using the quadratic model the residuals and quantiles fit very well, there were no problems with normality, and there were no exceptionally influential points. Assuming each measurement has independence, our model is: \[ Speed_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1\times{StepRate_i} +\beta_2\times{StepRate_i^2}+\epsilon_i \], Where \[\epsilon_i \;\tilde\;\; iid\;\:N(0,\sigma^2)\] This model explains 86% of the variation in the data.

2.8 Executive Summary

We collected data on the speed and step rate of an athlete during a football game. Our goal was to find if step rate was related to the athletes speed on the pitch, so that we could predict the speed for a given step rate.

Our data did not agree with the typical linear relationship, unlike the data we took on a running track. Instead, we found that there was a quadratic relationship between speed and step rate. As the athletes step rate increased, so did his speed. However, the rate of increase was not constant. His speed increased faster for lower step rates and increased slower when step rate was already high.

This suggests that, unlike the track, step rate is not a great predictor of speed and other conditions need to be considered. For example, it might be that on a football field more agility and control of the ball is needed, requiring more steps.

This differs from the track, where we fit a linear model. The difference in priorities from the athlete between the scenarios allows him to focus purely on speed, rather than any precise control.
